Note:
PLATFORM ABSTRACTION LAYER: Machine Code Generation (Generic Encoder API)

This file is the platform-agnostic machine-code encoder dispatcher. It is the
runtime-callable foundation that the AOTT (All-Of-The-Time) optimizer uses to
emit native code at RUNTIME and that inline_asm consumes to lower assembly
fragments. It exposes a single, stable, ISA-independent encoder API and fans
each call out to the correct platform backend selected at compile time.

Dispatch model:
- Selection is a compile-time fold on the builtin `__TARGET_PLATFORM_INDEX__`.
  The compiler driver resolves (os, arch) to a fixed integer index and folds the
  ladder below to the single matching branch for the target being built, so the
  cross-platform import set carries zero runtime dispatch cost. This mirrors the
  reworked sibling dispatchers (syscall.runa, threading.runa, atomic.runa,
  register_map.runa) which all switch on `__TARGET_PLATFORM_INDEX__`.
- Each platform module exposes `<arch>_encode_*` delegates (e.g.
  linux_x86_64_encode_mov) that map the generic ops onto that platform's rich
  low-level encoders. This file never reimplements an encoding; it only routes.

Backend index mapping (shared with all sibling dispatchers):
  1=linux_x86_64, 2=linux_arm64, 3=linux_arm32, 4=mips32, 5=mips64,
  6=darwin_x86_64, 7=darwin_arm64, 8=freebsd_x64, 9=freebsd_arm64,
  10=netbsd_x64, 11=netbsd_arm64, 12=openbsd_x64, 13=openbsd_arm64,
  14=windows_x86_64, 15=windows_arm64, 16=powerpc, 17=riscv32, 18=riscv64
:End Note

Note:
=============================================================================
THE GENERIC ENCODER API CONTRACT (12 entry points)
=============================================================================

All operands are register ids and integer immediates/displacements; encoded
bytes are written into a caller-supplied code buffer (`buffer_ptr`) and the
number of bytes written (the instruction length) is returned. A return of 0
means "nothing encoded" and is treated as an encode error / unavailable-op by
callers. Register ids are the platform's own register numbering (the ids the
platform low-level encoders expect); AOTT/inline_asm obtain them from the
platform register map. The buffer must have room for at least the platform's
maximum instruction length (15 bytes on x86_64; 4 bytes on fixed-width RISC).

Abstract opcode ids (used by encode_instruction / get_instruction_length),
honored identically by every platform delegate:
  1  = MOV    operand_a=dest_reg, operand_b=src_reg
  2  = ADD    operand_a=dest_reg, operand_b=src_reg   (dest <- dest + src)
  3  = SUB    operand_a=dest_reg, operand_b=src_reg   (dest <- dest - src)
  4  = LOAD   operand_a=dest_reg, operand_b=base_reg, operand_c=displacement
  5  = STORE  operand_a=src_reg,  operand_b=base_reg, operand_c=displacement
  6  = JUMP   operand_a=rel_offset (byte displacement to target)
  7  = CALL   operand_a=rel_offset (byte displacement to target)
  8  = RETURN
  9  = NOP
  10 = MOVI   operand_a=dest_reg, operand_b=immediate
  11 = CMP    operand_a=reg1, operand_b=reg2
  12 = PUSH   operand_a=reg
  13 = POP    operand_a=reg

The 12 entry points:
  1.  encode_instruction(opcode_id, operand_a, operand_b, operand_c, buffer_ptr) -> length
        Encode one instruction selected by abstract opcode id. The universal
        emit primitive for AOTT/inline_asm.
  2.  get_instruction_length(opcode_id, operand_a, operand_b, operand_c) -> length
        Encoded length in bytes without committing to the caller buffer
        (variable-length targets encode into scratch; fixed-width return 4).
  3.  encode_add(dest_reg, src_reg, value, buffer_ptr) -> length
        dest_reg <- dest_reg + src_reg. `value` is reserved for the uniform
        cross-platform register/immediate-form signature.
  4.  encode_sub(dest_reg, src_reg, value, buffer_ptr) -> length
        dest_reg <- dest_reg - src_reg.
  5.  encode_mov(dest_reg, src_reg, buffer_ptr) -> length
        dest_reg <- src_reg (register to register).
  6.  encode_load(dest_reg, base_reg, displacement, buffer_ptr) -> length
        dest_reg <- [base_reg + displacement].
  7.  encode_store(src_reg, base_reg, displacement, buffer_ptr) -> length
        [base_reg + displacement] <- src_reg.
  8.  encode_jump(rel_offset, buffer_ptr) -> length
        Unconditional jump to pc + rel_offset.
  9.  encode_call(rel_offset, buffer_ptr) -> length
        Call pc + rel_offset.
  10. encode_return(buffer_ptr) -> length
        Function return.
  11. get_nop_instruction(buffer_ptr) -> length
        Encode a NOP for padding/alignment.
  12. optimize_instruction_sequence(instructions_ptr, count) -> optimized_count
        Peephole pass over an array of `count` 32-byte instruction records
        (fields: opcode_id, operand_a, operand_b, operand_c, each little-endian
        8 bytes). Rewrites redundant operations to NOP in place (preserving
        record count and branch offsets) and returns the number of records
        optimized. Returns 0 for an already-optimal sequence (correct identity).
:End Note

